---
import { Heading, Markdown } from '@splendidlabz/astro'
---

<section>
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="vertical">
      <Heading class="gap-4" center>
        <h2 class="h1 max-w-[12em] text-zorange-500">
          Images Shouldn't Be Complicated
        </h2>
      </Heading>

      <div class="prose-responsive max-w-narrow mx-auto">
        <Markdown
          content="
    We didn't have to worry much about images in the old days. We just had to minify the image and use a standard `<img>` tag.

      But fast forward till today. Images have gotten complex. Now we have to:

      - Handle responsive images with `srcset`
      - Improve image performance with image formats like `avif` and `webp`
      - Use `picture` and `source` tags to support image formats
      - Do art direction with `<picture>` instead of simply hiding the image
      - Lazy load images so they don't block rendering
      - Let images have `width` and `height` attributes to make Google lighthouse audit happy for SEO...

      I'd say we drop all of that complexity into a single component --- prebuilt and ready to use. And this does everything above for you.

      ```
      <Image src='/src/assets/image.png' alt='image' />
      ```
    "
        />

        <!-- prettier-ignore -->
        <Markdown>
          Astro's image tooling is good. But it only covers the simple case.

          The moment you need a caption, you're writing custom markup. Background images skip optimization entirely. Art direction means hand-writing `<picture>` tags. Framework components can't access `astro:assets`. Animated GIFs stay heavy. SVG icons have no consistent pattern. CI builds choke on hundreds of images.

          Each problem has a solution. But you have to find them individually, implement them separately, and re-figure them out on the next project.

          This module is the system.

          You know how `Image` works. You've read the docs. Maybe you've even gotten `srcset` working.

          Then the real project starts.

          You need different crops on mobile and desktop --- and there's no clean way to do art direction without writing 15 lines of `<picture>` markup by hand.

          You need an optimized background image in CSS --- but `astro:assets` only works with components, not `background-image`. So you skip optimization or write a hack.

          You have images inside MDX content --- and they render at full width on every device. No automatic `srcset`. Mobile visitors download 2MB hero images on cellular.

          You're using React or Svelte components --- and they can't access `astro:assets` at all. You end up passing image data through props from wrapper files. It works, but it's fragile.

          Then your CI build starts choking. 200 images, each generating 6 sizes. Memory spikes. Builds timeout. Vercel complains.

          None of this is about not knowing the Astro image API. It's about not having a system for when each approach applies.

          That's what this module gives you.
        </Markdown>
      </div>
    </div>
  </
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
